<TITLE> Fleming stands firm for New Zealand </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 CENTURION, South Africa, Nov 18 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Stephen Fleming stood firm for New Zealand with an unbeaten 54 as South Africa strode towards victory at tea on the third day of the second test on Sunday. New Zealand limped to the interval on 110-4 in their second innings, 85 runs short of making South Africa bat again. Fleming hit nine fours and a six for New Zealand's top score. Fast bowler Mark Gillespie took five wickets for 136 on his debut as South Africa were dismissed for 383 in their first innings. Hashim Amla, who scored 176 not out in the first test in Johannesburg, added another century with a disciplined 103 but South Africa lost five wickets for 50 runs to the second new ball to stumble to 332-8 after resuming on 272-3. Amla's patient innings ended when he drove uppishly at a delivery from medium pacer Iain O'Brien and was caught by a diving Michael Papps in the covers. New Zealand's progress was held up by a spirited stand of 51 for the ninth wicket between Dale Steyn and Andre Nel, who both scored 25. The visitors' slipped to 9-2 in their second innings when fast bowler Steyn trapped Lou Vincent (4) and Papps (1) in front. Fleming and Scott Styris combined in a stand of 60 that ended when Styris (29) edged a ball from fast bowler Jacques Kallis to AB de Villiers at second slip. New Zealand were 78-4 when Ross Taylor was run out for eight by Amla's flick on to the stumps from short leg
